<paper id="1846779381"><title>Update Rules in Datalog Programs</title><year>1995</year><authors><author org="Université de Paris — Sud" id="2321600990">M. Halfeld Ferrari Alves</author><author org="Université de Paris-Sud" id="2917365365">Dominique Laurent</author><author org="Université de Paris — Sud" id="171306905">Nicolas Spyratos</author></authors><n_citation>8</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>115237046</reference><reference>1509971077</reference><reference>1511711492</reference><reference>1672891595</reference><reference>1756530980</reference><reference>1968513265</reference><reference>2008294142</reference><reference>2010160994</reference><reference>2067326626</reference><reference>2091849010</reference></references><venue id="1201110412" type="C">International Conference on Logic Programming</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-59487-6_6</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.45261">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.45835">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.43072">Predicate (grammar)</keyword><keyword weight="0.59911">Datalog</keyword><keyword weight="0.49103">Semantics</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We consider Datalogneg databases containing two kinds of rules: update rules and query rules. We regard update rules as constraints, all consequences of which must hold in the database until a new update. We introduce a semantics framework for database updates and query answering based on the well-founded semantics. In this framework, updating over intensional predicates is deterministic.</abstract></paper>